## Behavioral and Social Effects of Media

### Influence on Behavior and Social Norms

Media not only affects perceptions but also behaviors. The **behavioral component of the third-person effect** suggests that individuals may act to regulate or censor media content they perceive as harmful to others. For example, parents might restrict their children’s media exposure despite believing that other children are more influenced by negative content ([Perloff, 2002](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285804881_Media_effects_Advances_in_theory_and_research)).

Long-term exposure to media, especially violent content, has been linked to increased aggression and desensitization. Studies indicate that repeated viewing of violence can make individuals less sensitive to real-life violence and reduce their fight-or-flight responses ([UKEssays, 2015](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/media/effects-of-media-on-personality-media-essay.php)). This desensitization may contribute to normalization of aggressive behavior and altered social interactions.

### Media’s Role in Shaping Personality and Identity

Media contributes significantly to the development of personality traits and social identity. Through repeated exposure to idealized images and narratives, especially in Hollywood and advertising, individuals—particularly adolescents—may internalize unrealistic standards of beauty and success. This can lead to lowered self-esteem, body dissatisfaction, and mental health issues such as anorexia or depression ([Helton & Beran, 2015](https://prezi.com/fq6_h-eyfddr/effects-of-media-on-society-individuals/)).

Conversely, media can also have positive effects by increasing knowledge, relaxation, and social connectedness. Educational programs and informative content enable skill development and awareness of social issues, contributing to personal growth ([LetUsFindOut, n.d.](https://www.letusfindout.com/how-does-media-affect-our-lives/)).

