## Mechanisms of Media Influence

### Selective Exposure and Retention

The **minimal-effects model** posits that media reinforce existing attitudes rather than change them drastically. People tend to engage in selective exposure, choosing media that aligns with their beliefs, and selective retention, remembering information that supports their views ([Quizlet, n.d.](https://quizlet.com/81085379/jomc101-chapter-15-flash-cards/)). This model explains why media effects are often subtle and mediated by individual differences.

### Framing and Information Processing

Media frames influence how audiences interpret information. By emphasizing certain aspects of a story, media shape public understanding and policy debates. For instance, framing educational controversies in a particular light can normalize specific viewpoints among policymakers and the public ([Entman, 1989](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231746722_How_the_Media_Affect_What_People_Think_An_Information_Processing_Approach)).

